{"cursor":"9235","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"A 'biodiversity hotspot' is a biogeographic region with a significant reservoir\nof biodiversity that is under threat from humans.\n\nThe concept of biodiversity hotspots was originated by Norman Myers in two\narticles in âThe Environmentalistâ (1988), Myers, N. The\nEnvironmentalist 8 187-208 (1988) & 1990 Myers, N. The\nEnvironmentalist 10 243-256 (1990) revised after thorough analysis by\nMyers and others in âHotspots: Earthâs Biologically Richest and Most\nEndangered Terrestrial Ecoregionsâ. Russell A. Mittermeier, Norman Myers\nand Cristina Goettsch Mittermeier, Hotspots: Earth's Biologically Richest\nand Most Endangered Terrestrial Ecoregions, Conservation International, 2000\nISBN 978-968-6397-58-1\n\nTo qualify as a biodiversity hotspot on Myers 2000 edition of the hotspot-map,\na region must meet two strict criteria: it must contain at least 0.5% or 1,500\nspecies of vascular plants as endemics, and it has to have lost at least 70% of\nits primary vegetation. Myers, N. et al. Nature (journal) 403, 853â858\n(2000) Around the world, 25 areas qualify under this definition, with\nnine other possible candidates. These sites support nearly 60% of the world's\nplant, bird, mammal, reptile, and amphibian species, with a very high share of\nendemic species.\n","linknr":223,"url":"Biodiversity_hotspot","recorded":1374763602,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Biodiversity_hotspot&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Biodiversity_hotspot&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7